{"batch":"cross_module_architecture","batch_index":15,"assessments":{"cross_module_architecture":42.0},"dimension_notes":{"cross_module_architecture":{"evidence":["The repository keeps multiple top-level scripts that each re-implement the same play-by-play boundary logic instead of sharing a domain module: `step2_build_possessions.py:38-128`, `build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:63-165`, `categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:66-171`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:42-100`, and `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:88-153` all rebuild possession grouping and defensive-foul classification from raw JSON.","Cross-script coordination happens through hard-coded file names and implicit CSV schemas rather than imports or typed interfaces: `build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:5-7,168-175` writes `possession_model_table_okc_mil.csv`, while `calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py:3-4,47-56` reads that file and assumes `L_t/F_t/N_t` columns by name.","Architecture drift is already visible in retained checkpoint copies under `.ipynb_checkpoints`: the live files use global possession windows (`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:134-150`, `categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:148-167`), but the checkpoint copies still implement earlier defensive-team-window logic (`.ipynb_checkpoints/build_possession_model_table_okc_mil-checkpoint.py:134-167`, `.ipynb_checkpoints/categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil-checkpoint.py:148-169`).","The README advertises `step2_build_possessions.py` as the current possession builder (`README.md:4-10`), but downstream WMI scripts do not depend on it; they independently fetch and regroup raw play-by-play again (`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:63-165`, `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:42-100`). That leaves two parallel possession architectures with no enforced boundary between parsing and metric computation.","The project log documents repeated reversions between global-window and team-filtered logic (`nba-whistle-project-log.md:34-58`), and the codebase still contains both branches of that design in active files plus checkpoint copies, which raises the blast radius of future definition changes."] ,"impact_scope":"codebase","fix_scope":"architectural_change","confidence":"high"}},"issues":[{"dimension":"cross_module_architecture","identifier":"duplicate_wmi_pipeline_logic","summary":"Core possession and foul-classification rules are duplicated across multiple scripts instead of living behind one shared boundary.","related_files":["step2_build_possessions.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py"],"evidence":["`step2_build_possessions.py:38-128` builds possession groups and counts defensive fouls from raw play-by-play.","`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:63-165` repeats the same fetch/sort/group/classify flow to produce WMI-ready rows.","`categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:66-171` repeats the same grouping and foul filtering again for another output shape.","`calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:42-100` implements yet another copy of the same possession-to-`F_t/L_t/N_t/M_t` pipeline, and `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:88-153` maintains a separate historical-season variant."],"suggestion":"Extract a shared `pbp_pipeline` module that owns fetch, possession grouping, defensive-foul classification, and WMI feature generation. Make the current scripts thin entry points that call that module with different output formatters.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"codebase","fix_scope":"architectural_change","root_cause_cluster":"missing_shared_pipeline"},{"dimension":"cross_module_architecture","identifier":"csv_contracts_replace_module_boundaries","summary":"Scripts depend on each other through hard-coded filenames and column names, so the workflow boundary exists only in ad hoc CSV contracts.","related_files":["build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py","Plan for WMI - Ryan Kalfus (2026).md","README.md"],"evidence":["`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:5-7,152-175` hard-codes the output path and emitted columns.","`calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py:3-4,47-56` hard-codes the input path and only validates that `L_t`, `F_t`, and `N_t` happen to exist.","`Plan for WMI - Ryan Kalfus (2026).md:68-74` lists output files as the project workflow artifacts, which shows the orchestration contract lives in documentation and filenames rather than code."],"suggestion":"Create a small package API for the pipeline stages, such as `build_model_table(game_id) -> DataFrame` and `calculate_rawgame(model_table) -> dict`, then have CLI wrappers write CSVs only at the outer boundary. Keep schema definitions in one place so producers and consumers cannot silently drift.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"missing_shared_pipeline"},{"dimension":"cross_module_architecture","identifier":"stale_checkpoint_logic_blurs_boundaries","summary":"Notebook checkpoint Python files preserve older versions of the same workflow, so obsolete architectural paths still sit beside the live code.","related_files":[".ipynb_checkpoints/build_possession_model_table_okc_mil-checkpoint.py",".ipynb_checkpoints/categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil-checkpoint.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py"],"evidence":["The active `build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:134-150` computes global last2/next2 windows, but `.ipynb_checkpoints/build_possession_model_table_okc_mil-checkpoint.py:134-167` still computes defensive-team-filtered windows and different column names.","The active `categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:148-167` emits `L_t/F_t/N_t/M_t`, while `.ipynb_checkpoints/categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil-checkpoint.py:148-169` emits older `def_foul_called_in_last2_defensive_team_possessions` fields instead.","Because these are executable `.py` files in the repo root tree, they act like compatibility-shim paths with no clear ownership or suppression boundary."],"suggestion":"Exclude `.ipynb_checkpoints` from production code review/runtime, or remove these checkpoint `.py` files entirely after promoting notebook changes into the canonical scripts. If historical variants matter, move them into a clearly named `archive/` area with a README explaining they are non-authoritative.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"stale_parallel_variants"},{"dimension":"cross_module_architecture","identifier":"parallel_possession_builders_without_owner","summary":"The repo maintains two different possession-builder entry points for the same domain, but downstream code does not consume a single canonical parser.","related_files":["README.md","step2_build_possessions.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py"],"evidence":["`README.md:4-10` presents `step2_build_possessions.py` as the current possession builder and `possessions_step2_sample.csv` as the current sample output.","`step2_build_possessions.py:38-128` builds a possession table with `start_time/end_time/defensive_foul_count`.","`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:63-165` does not consume that parser output; it re-fetches raw play-by-play and rebuilds possession groups itself for WMI modeling."],"suggestion":"Choose one canonical ownership boundary for possession parsing. Either make `step2_build_possessions.py` the reusable parser that all downstream WMI code imports, or fold its logic into a shared module and retire the separate script as a standalone source of truth.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"architectural_change","root_cause_cluster":"missing_shared_pipeline"}],"retrospective":{"root_causes":["The codebase is organized as task-specific scripts rather than a shared analytics package, so each new workflow copied domain logic instead of depending on a stable internal API.","Experimentation around WMI definitions happened by creating new script variants and reruns, but there is no retirement boundary for superseded implementations."],"likely_symptoms":["duplicate_wmi_pipeline_logic","parallel_possession_builders_without_owner","stale_checkpoint_logic_blurs_boundaries"],"possible_false_positives":[]}}
